# Rebuild plan — {{site_name}}

This plan is tailored to **`{{target_stack}}`**. It assumes you
have already read `AGENT_GUIDE.md` and `INDEX.json`.

## Step 1 — Project scaffolding

{{#stack:nextjs-tailwind-shadcn}}
- Use the App Router with one route per entry in `meta/urls.txt`.
- Map design tokens into `tailwind.config.ts`:
  - `theme.colors` ← `design-tokens.json.palette` (group by `roles`).
  - `theme.fontFamily` ← `design-tokens.json.typography[].font_family`.
  - `theme.spacing` ← unique tokens from
    `design-tokens.json.spacing`.
  - `theme.borderRadius` ← `design-tokens.json.radii`.
  - `theme.boxShadow` ← `design-tokens.json.shadows`.
- Add fonts via `next/font/local` from `assets/fonts/` if the
  inventory is non-empty, otherwise pull the closest match from
  Google Fonts.
- shadcn/ui components: install only the primitives required by
  the captured sections. Resist building a full kit.
{{/stack}}

{{#stack:vite-react}}
- One route per entry in `meta/urls.txt` via `react-router`.
- Tokens become CSS variables in `:root` (one var per palette
  entry, per spacing step, etc.). Import once in `main.tsx`.
- Use `vite-plugin-fonts` (or a `@font-face` block) for any local
  font files in `assets/fonts/`.
{{/stack}}

{{#stack:astro}}
- One `src/pages/*.astro` per entry in `meta/urls.txt`.
- Tokens → `src/styles/tokens.css` as custom properties.
- Astro components per section; use island hydration only where
  `observations.md` documents an interaction.
{{/stack}}

{{#stack:plain-html}}
- One `.html` file per entry in `meta/urls.txt`, sharing a single
  `styles.css` with `design-tokens.json` mapped to CSS variables.
- Self-host fonts from `assets/fonts/` via `@font-face`.
{{/stack}}

## Step 2 — Section components

For every page, iterate `pages/<slug>/sections.json` in order.
Each entry tells you:

- `id` — stable identifier; use as the component name.
- `bbox.<viewport>` — expected dimensions per viewport.
- `dom_html_byte_range` / `raw_html_byte_range` — slice the HTML
  files at these offsets to see the source markup.
- `copy_byte_range` — slice `copy.md` for the text content.
- `dominant_tokens` — the design tokens observed inside the
  section. Use these instead of resampling.
- `screenshot_crops.<viewport>` — visual reference per viewport.

Build one component per section. Re-use the dominant tokens via
the global token mapping from Step 1.

## Step 3 — Asset wiring

For every asset referenced by a section, look it up in
`assets/manifest.json` and import / serve it from the local
path. The manifest's `referencing_pages` field tells you whether
the asset is shared across pages (move it to a shared layout) or
page-specific (keep it scoped).

## Step 4 — Motion and micro-interactions

`design-tokens.json.motion` records observed `transition` and
`animation` values. Apply them at the component level.

For anything that is not a CSS-level transition — scroll
reveals, hover sequences, view-transition handoffs — read
`observations.md`. If `observations.md` is empty for a behaviour
you can see in the screenshots, **stop and ask** before
inventing motion.

## Step 5 — Cross-check

Before declaring a page done, compare your build to the
captured screenshot at every viewport:

- `pages/<slug>/desktop.png` should match the desktop build.
- `pages/<slug>/mobile.png` should match the mobile build.

For each `sections.json[].screenshot_crops.<viewport>`, the
matching section in your build should look the same.

## Step 6 — What you should NOT do

- **Do not copy assets or copy text verbatim into shipped
  product code.** The dossier is reference-only — produce
  original art and original copy.
- **Do not sample colors or fonts directly from the screenshots.**
  Use `design-tokens.json` — it has frequency counts and roles.
- **Do not paste JS from `assets/js-urls.json`** — they are
  minified framework bundles with no design-reference value.
